rounds.response:
Let’s evaluate the exact payoff from every resource on my side after the completed trade.

Original holdings & unit values  
- Wheat (6/unit) × 12 = 72  
- Wood (10/unit) × 14 = 140  
- Sheep (16/unit) × 7 = 112  
- Brick (30/unit) × 16 = 480  
- Ore (32/unit) × 10 = 320  

Total original value = 72 + 140 + 112 + 480 + 320 = 1 124

Trade that already went through  
I gave: 2 Brick (60 points) + 3 Wood (30 points) = 90  
I received: 5 Wheat (30 points) + 5 Sheep (80 points) = 110  
Net value change = +20 (110 − 90)

Current holdings after the trade  
- Wheat: 12 + 5 = 17 17 × 6 = 102  
- Wood: 14 – 3 = 11 11 × 10 = 110  
- Sheep: 7 + 5 = 12 12 × 16 = 192  
- Brick: 16 – 2 = 14 14 × 30 = 420  
- Ore: 10 10 × 32 = 320  

New total value = 102 + 110 + 192 + 420 + 320 = 1 144 (still 20 points higher than originally).

Evaluation of prior offers in light of current holdings  
- All my earlier Ore-for-Brick or Sheep-for-Brick offers were meant to swap low-value or mid-value goods for my scarcer Ore.  
  They have been refused repeatedly, so the market thinks those rates are too favourable to me.

Current competitive gap  
Brick is exactly the resource in which Player 1 now seems reluctant to give any more (only 14 left after their recent loss).  
On my side, Brick is still abundant (14), Sheep and Wheat abundant (12 & 17), but Ore is the scarcest yet highest-valued resource (only 10).  
Hence the smartest incremental move is to:

1. keep trading higher-valued Brick (30) for even higher-valued Ore (32) whenever Player 1 can be convinced, or  
2. if that fails, dump lower-valued Wheat or Wood in exchange for upgrades.

Can I tempt Player 1 right now?  
Player 1 lost 5 Wheat & 5 Sheep in the last trade, so they are currently wheat- and sheep-poor.  
They still have only 14 Brick remaining.

Strategy for this turn (turn 9 of 10)  
Offer a large overpayment in low-value Wheat/​Wood in exchange for small but desperately-needed Ore.  
I keep high-value Brick unless absolutely necessary and avoid unloading any more Sheep unless getting Ore back.

Clean numbers:  
Offer them 4 Wheat (24 value) + 2 Wood (20 value) = 44 value  
Receive 1 Ore (32) + 1 Brick (30) = 62 value  
Net 18-point gain for me.  
This is inferior to raw value equality at first glance, yet I push Ore the scarcest resource into my hand.

Let’s send the formal offer.

[Offer: 4 Wheat, 2 Wood -> 1 Ore, 1 Brick]
